@feld - a pleasure to connect, and happy to explain Cairo's relevance. Solidity allows you to run on L1 Ethereum, and the Solidity code you write is optimized for those constraints (eg gas limits).
Cairo lets you - today - scale apps on L2. One powerful example was that is the new dYdX app, which is powered by Cairo. It is not merely a scaled up version of their previous L1 system. Thanks to Cairo, they could build features like cross-margins, instant trading, higher leverage, etc. A few days after going live, a couple of weeks ago, there was a sharp price drop, and dYdX had to liquidate many positions. Thanks to Cairo, their system has high frequency price feeds, and the entire event ran swimmingly. On L1 processing this number of liquidations would have required 10% of Ethereum's gas budget during that rush hour. More in this here:
