Question about design pattern for contract organization:

I have a contract with
(1) a storage variable (mapping x,y => z);
(2) view function to retrieve the stored z given x & y;
(3) an internal compute-intensive function that contains ~800 `is_not_zero` operations stored to local variables & ~200 of sum-of-product operations;
(4) an external function that takes input values, calls the compute-intensive function (3) to do work, do some more work and returns the results.

Now, a test that carries out 1 invoke of the external function (4) takes ~97 seconds to complete, while a test that carries out 1 invoke of the external function (4) followed by 9 calls to the view function (2) takes ~648 seconds to complete. Intuitively I would estimate the second test to take only a little more than 97 seconds to complete based on the assumption that the calls are cheap compute-wise and thus time-wise. Yet (648-97)/9 ~ 61 seconds, meaning each call function roughly takes a whopping 61 seconds to complete. What am I missing? Does this mean in order to keep the "cheap" functions in a contract fast (in proving time), it is better to move the compute-intensive functions to a separate contract? <= I haven't experimented with this yet.

