@martriay @hubsmoke @CalabashSquash - This is indeed a problem currently. I don't think there is a "clever" contract design that can prevent it. 
Currently the plan is to change the account model to address (among other things) this exact problem. We are working closely with the ERC-4337 team, but the idea is to separate the transaction handling into two parts - validation and execution, and to add nonce to the contract state. The problem you are describing will be solved since the transaction will fail at the validation step and won't "burn" the hash as it is doing today. Once the transaction will pass the validation step, the nonce will be consumed regardless if the execution has succeeded or not (which is quite similar to Ethereum in that sense).

We are at the final stage of finalising the proposal and we will post it once it's ready.

